WEBVTT

00:00:00.520 --> 00:00:01.800
So, hi everyone.

00:00:01.800 --> 00:00:04.600
As a core Quarto developer, I know firsthand

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:07.260
all the amazing features that we built into Quarto

00:00:07.260 --> 00:00:10.040
and that we document in quarto.org.

00:00:10.040 --> 00:00:13.320
But I also know all the advanced features

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:16.000
that Quarto offers and can help you, users,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.400
go beyond the limits of Quarto.

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:21.520
And we do document this feature also on the websites,

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:23.680
but I personally know that it's

00:00:24.799 --> 00:00:27.760
hard to explain, although there is like,

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:29.940
we need to be so thorough, there are a lot to explain,

00:00:29.940 --> 00:00:32.619
and so I can definitely relate if it's hard

00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:36.060
to feel confident trying to use those features

00:00:36.060 --> 00:00:37.740
or even knowing what they could use for,

00:00:37.740 --> 00:00:39.340
like they could seem so advanced.

00:00:39.340 --> 00:00:44.060
And so, today, in this talk, I want to bridge that gap.

00:00:44.060 --> 00:00:46.480
I want to give you the foundational knowledge that you need

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:48.500
so that you can consider Lua filters,

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:50.500
one of these advanced features,

00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:53.820
for your own problems and solutions.

00:00:53.820 --> 00:00:56.619
And hopefully, after, you will be more at ease

00:00:56.619 --> 00:00:59.259
to navigate the advanced documentation that we offer.

00:01:00.139 --> 00:01:02.900
So why would you need Lua filter in the first place?

00:01:04.419 --> 00:01:09.300
When we use a tool, we want this tool to solve our problems

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:12.980
but sometimes this tool doesn't offer the solution we need

00:01:12.980 --> 00:01:16.099
and this is what I call the I'm stuck problem.

00:01:16.099 --> 00:01:17.620
So maybe you ask yourself, like,

00:01:17.620 --> 00:01:21.660
can I Quarto do X that I need for my organization report?

00:01:21.660 --> 00:01:23.739
Or is this possible to do Y?

00:01:23.739 --> 00:01:28.099
Documentation says I can do Z but I really need Y.

00:01:28.099 --> 00:01:30.379
And so, usually, as a user,

00:01:30.379 --> 00:01:32.860
those problems are a huge pain point for you

00:01:32.860 --> 00:01:36.860
but they may be so specific that you may ask on forums

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:39.540
but nobody has a solution or maybe it's like

00:01:39.540 --> 00:01:43.220
not enough generic to be built in ever into the tools.

00:01:43.220 --> 00:01:44.540
But that's not a problem.

00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:47.220
You should be able to solve your own problem

00:01:47.220 --> 00:01:49.779
with some solution and this is where Lua filter

00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:52.620
with Quarto come in.

00:01:52.620 --> 00:01:55.739
And when you think about it, as a R or Python user

00:01:55.739 --> 00:01:59.220
or doing data analysis code, when you have a problem

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:01.059
that some of the package you use

00:02:01.059 --> 00:02:04.220
or what you are trying to use, you can't do it,

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:07.339
then the thing you will do is write probably some function.

00:02:07.339 --> 00:02:09.899
So maybe some of you will write a full-blown package

00:02:09.899 --> 00:02:12.220
at first for every specific problem

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:15.380
but usually the first step is to write a single function,

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:16.940
put them in script, a second one,

00:02:16.940 --> 00:02:20.339
and then solve your own problem as this goes.

00:02:20.339 --> 00:02:23.660
And in the Quarto ecosystem, it can be very similar.

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:25.699
So you have a problem to solve,

00:02:25.699 --> 00:02:28.300
this time inside your Quarto document

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:30.899
and you may have heard about Quarto extensions

00:02:30.899 --> 00:02:33.619
as a way to extend the capabilities of Quarto.

00:02:34.619 --> 00:02:39.460
And really, you no need to go like further

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:42.580
than doing some scripts and in the Quarto ecosystem,

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:45.539
those scripts will be the Lua filters

00:02:45.539 --> 00:02:48.100
which will contain some Lua functions.

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:49.940
And you don't need to be a full

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:51.660
like Quarto extension developer.

00:02:51.820 --> 00:02:54.940
As a user, you should be able to use those tools.

00:02:54.940 --> 00:02:57.460
And this is what we'll see today,

00:02:57.460 --> 00:03:00.419
what Lua filters can be used for, how they work,

00:03:00.419 --> 00:03:03.619
and how you can start writing your own functions.

00:03:03.619 --> 00:03:05.419
So let's take a very simple example

00:03:05.419 --> 00:03:08.059
for the purpose of explaining all that.

00:03:08.059 --> 00:03:11.580
This user works in an organization that is called Acme Inc.

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:14.619
And that requires him to use the trademark symbol

00:03:14.619 --> 00:03:19.460
of the brand each time the company's name in a report.

00:03:19.460 --> 00:03:21.139
And so this can be really tedious,

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:23.020
if you are a Windows user like me,

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:24.460
like adding a trademark symbol

00:03:24.460 --> 00:03:26.619
is like a weird combination of keys.

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:30.179
So it's a normal question to ask,

00:03:30.179 --> 00:03:31.500
can this be automated?

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:34.220
And if you were doing that in our analysis, for example,

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:37.179
you may be writing a function that look like this.

00:03:37.179 --> 00:03:39.059
You would find a way to split the text

00:03:39.059 --> 00:03:40.619
and then look for the text.

00:03:40.619 --> 00:03:42.500
And if this is like the name, Acme Inc.,

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:45.100
then you would append the trademark symbol to it

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:47.339
and return the modified or unmodified value.

00:03:48.339 --> 00:03:50.820
If you want to do that in Quarto,

00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:52.699
to process the Quarto documents,

00:03:52.699 --> 00:03:54.580
then this would look like this.

00:03:55.979 --> 00:03:58.300
It may be the first time that you are seeing Lua,

00:03:58.300 --> 00:04:03.100
so the logo you see is the Lua logo.

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:04.699
So this is a Lua function,

00:04:04.699 --> 00:04:08.059
and this is like a screen of the full Lua filters

00:04:08.059 --> 00:04:09.820
that will aim to do that.

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:11.660
So it's a single function.

00:04:11.660 --> 00:04:13.619
And maybe it's new to you, this language,

00:04:13.619 --> 00:04:15.419
maybe there is some syntax you don't understand,

00:04:15.419 --> 00:04:17.100
and we will go deeper into it,

00:04:17.859 --> 00:04:20.140
but the important part is that this is a function.

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:23.140
Lua offers functional programming.

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:24.660
Indentation matters.

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:26.579
And you can find some construct,

00:04:26.579 --> 00:04:31.500
like the if then text and the return function.

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:34.140
So this function look quite similar to the R version.

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:37.899
So to understand how this function can apply

00:04:37.899 --> 00:04:39.339
on the document to modify it,

00:04:39.339 --> 00:04:43.420
we need to take a broader view of the Quarto processing.

00:04:44.899 --> 00:04:46.859
So when you write a QMD document,

00:04:47.619 --> 00:04:48.459
the first step of the processing

00:04:48.459 --> 00:04:50.619
will be computation engine.

00:04:50.619 --> 00:04:52.540
And so Quarto will run your code,

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.260
usually so your R, Python, Julia code,

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:57.739
and using the correct engine,

00:04:57.739 --> 00:04:59.899
and produce an intermediate markdown file.

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:03.820
And this is the first step where you, as a user,

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:05.660
you can interfere with the processing,

00:05:05.660 --> 00:05:08.940
using some custom function with your language of choice

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:10.820
in this part.

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:14.059
The second step of the processing

00:05:14.059 --> 00:05:16.820
is writing to the desired output.

00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:19.579
So you may want a PDF report, an HTML report.

00:05:19.579 --> 00:05:21.700
And so this is where Pandoc comes into play.

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:23.859
So Quarto will call Pandoc.

00:05:23.859 --> 00:05:28.579
And this part of the processing can also be customized.

00:05:28.579 --> 00:05:30.299
And this time, it can be customized

00:05:30.299 --> 00:05:33.260
using Lua function inside Lua filters.

00:05:35.019 --> 00:05:38.820
And Quarto extensively uses Lua filter inside

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:40.299
to bring the features that you see.

00:05:40.299 --> 00:05:42.380
So all the features that you see in Quarto

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:43.779
that doesn't exist in Pandoc,

00:05:43.779 --> 00:05:45.500
for those who know Pandoc,

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:48.420
they probably are made using some Lua filters.

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.220
We also use Lua filters to modify

00:05:51.220 --> 00:05:53.339
the default behavior of Pandoc.

00:05:53.339 --> 00:05:56.260
And as a user, you can insert your own processing

00:05:56.260 --> 00:05:57.980
into there in form of functions.

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:01.779
And so how does this function can apply

00:06:01.779 --> 00:06:04.700
on the text from your document?

00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:06.579
And the specific thing is that Quarto

00:06:06.579 --> 00:06:08.700
does not really work on the text itself.

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:10.579
As you can see, like maybe you think

00:06:10.579 --> 00:06:12.700
it's using regex or something like that.

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:13.540
Not at all.

00:06:13.540 --> 00:06:15.980
So under the hood, we need to look into there.

00:06:15.980 --> 00:06:17.940
And this is an abstract representation.

00:06:19.859 --> 00:06:22.579
And so this is what we call the Pandoc abstract syntax tree.

00:06:22.579 --> 00:06:24.380
So it's not something easy to explain,

00:06:24.380 --> 00:06:26.299
but I hope like this simple schematic

00:06:26.299 --> 00:06:28.619
will give you like the right amount

00:06:28.619 --> 00:06:29.980
of understanding about that.

00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:32.980
So there is a full document that you have

00:06:32.980 --> 00:06:33.980
and that you see on the screen.

00:06:33.980 --> 00:06:36.179
And the first step of the reading part

00:06:36.179 --> 00:06:40.140
will be to split this document into blocks elements.

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:42.459
So the bigger elements.

00:06:42.459 --> 00:06:45.179
So it could be headers, paragraphs, some code blocks.

00:06:46.220 --> 00:06:48.140
And those elements are called blocks

00:06:48.140 --> 00:06:50.339
and they are like the branch of the tree.

00:06:50.339 --> 00:06:52.540
And the old document is a trunk.

00:06:53.619 --> 00:06:56.339
And each of these block will then be split

00:06:56.339 --> 00:06:59.299
into more granular elements, which are called the inlines.

00:06:59.299 --> 00:07:01.500
And so this will be the strings, some bold text,

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:03.100
some links, some emphasized word,

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:06.260
like some more granular element that are inside those blocks.

00:07:06.260 --> 00:07:08.579
And so those are called the inlines.

00:07:08.579 --> 00:07:11.100
And this is on that representation

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:12.660
that our function will apply.

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:14.700
So we come back to this function,

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:17.140
a Lua function inside the Lua filters

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:19.940
will apply on any node of this AST.

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:21.899
So this abstract representation.

00:07:21.899 --> 00:07:23.940
So our function here will apply

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:26.859
on all the strings in the document.

00:07:26.859 --> 00:07:28.260
And for each of these strings,

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:30.619
it will like look at the,

00:07:32.179 --> 00:07:33.940
it will take the string element as input

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:36.140
and it will look at the text information

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:40.899
to modify it in the output.

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:43.059
So either return the unmodified value

00:07:43.059 --> 00:07:44.619
or return the modified value.

00:07:44.619 --> 00:07:48.859
So it's quite similar to the R function that we've seen.

00:07:48.859 --> 00:07:52.820
And how this filter is used inside the document,

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:55.420
this is using a configuration key in your YAML editor.

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:57.299
So this is the filters key.

00:07:57.299 --> 00:08:00.700
And so this script can be added this way

00:08:00.700 --> 00:08:02.320
and then document will process.

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:06.859
And so here you see on the left, the source document,

00:08:06.859 --> 00:08:09.500
where you have like the insertion of the filter,

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:12.059
and then you see the name of the company from our user.

00:08:12.059 --> 00:08:15.059
And on the right, you see the rendered HTML output.

00:08:15.059 --> 00:08:18.019
And this output as the trademark symbol.

00:08:18.019 --> 00:08:21.540
And so this is a simple Lua filter that did this processing.

00:08:21.540 --> 00:08:23.420
So it modified the document.

00:08:23.420 --> 00:08:26.619
So we have a source and the render output.

00:08:26.619 --> 00:08:28.420
So this was a simple first example.

00:08:28.420 --> 00:08:31.459
And we'll see another one, which is maybe as simple,

00:08:31.459 --> 00:08:34.760
but will help us understand a bit more

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:38.380
how Lua function are written on the inside.

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:40.460
So this time, I will do it reverse.

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:42.539
I show you the results right now.

00:08:42.539 --> 00:08:45.260
So we have a Lua filter that's called card header.lua.

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:48.299
So the name, like maybe give hint on what it does.

00:08:48.299 --> 00:08:51.979
And we see we have some headers on the source.

00:08:51.979 --> 00:08:55.340
And those headers inside the output document

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:58.700
will have some spades or arts around them.

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:03.140
And so this Lua filter will do this modification.

00:09:03.140 --> 00:09:06.539
So maybe those of you already can know or guess

00:09:06.539 --> 00:09:07.799
what the Lua filter will be.

00:09:07.799 --> 00:09:11.960
But the first step is to look at the abstract representation.

00:09:11.960 --> 00:09:15.039
And for that, Krato offers a format

00:09:15.039 --> 00:09:16.960
that it's called a native format that you

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:19.840
can use either in the command line interface,

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:22.719
or you can use as any other format as a YAML key.

00:09:22.719 --> 00:09:25.400
And this will produce a .native file.

00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:29.080
And this file is the abstract syntax tree representation

00:09:29.080 --> 00:09:32.299
at the end of the processing, right before the writing

00:09:32.299 --> 00:09:35.239
step to the desired output, if you take the schematic.

00:09:35.239 --> 00:09:38.080
So this is the representation of the document.

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:39.200
And so it looks like that.

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:41.200
So this is a folded version.

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:44.440
But we can see that the main node is the document node.

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:46.320
This is all document.

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:50.760
And this document node is split into blocks.

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:55.200
Here we have a mix of header and paragraph.

00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:56.479
So header and paragraph.

00:09:56.479 --> 00:09:57.900
We have also a meta block, which is

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:00.000
a special block for metadata.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.960
And each of these blocks is then split into inlines.

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:06.520
And we can observe that in this format.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:08.840
So the first header has one inline,

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:10.359
which is a string introduction.

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:13.520
And the last yellow box shows a paragraph,

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:18.200
which is a mix of strings and space, a granular element.

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:22.159
So each of the nodes in the AST will

00:10:22.159 --> 00:10:24.400
have some contents in them.

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.140
But they will also have some information

00:10:27.140 --> 00:10:28.760
in the form of attributes.

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:29.640
So they can be ID.

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:30.440
They can be class.

00:10:30.440 --> 00:10:33.159
They can be key values.

00:10:33.159 --> 00:10:35.400
And so most of the nodes will have those information.

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:38.520
And some of them will have specific information.

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:42.520
And here our header have information of their level.

00:10:42.520 --> 00:10:45.520
So we have level two headers on the first arrow

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:49.340
and level three headers on the second arrow.

00:10:49.340 --> 00:10:51.640
And with those information, we can now

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:57.440
understand what the Lua function can be for this processing.

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:00.640
It's still a single function in Status Script.

00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:03.880
This function will target all header nodes.

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:08.119
But the processing will differ based on the level information

00:11:08.119 --> 00:11:10.080
that we have access to.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:12.640
And so if this is a level two header,

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:14.799
then we will add the space.

00:11:14.799 --> 00:11:16.400
And if this is a level three header,

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:18.320
then we will add the odds.

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:20.799
And how those elements are added,

00:11:20.799 --> 00:11:25.320
the content is modified using some API from Lua for Pandoc.

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:28.039
And the temple.insert function is a way

00:11:28.039 --> 00:11:33.440
to add some elements inside the contents of one of the nodes.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:36.919
And the pandoc.str function is coming from the Pandoc API.

00:11:36.919 --> 00:11:39.239
And it's a way to create new elements.

00:11:39.239 --> 00:11:40.239
So you can modify.

00:11:40.239 --> 00:11:43.159
You can create elements.

00:11:43.159 --> 00:11:45.239
So with those two simple examples,

00:11:45.239 --> 00:11:50.679
I hope you have now a better understanding of how Lua

00:11:50.679 --> 00:11:52.280
filter works and how you can write

00:11:52.280 --> 00:11:54.799
some for your own problems.

00:11:54.799 --> 00:11:57.880
So the first thing you will need is targeting nodes

00:11:57.880 --> 00:11:59.919
in the abstract syntax tree.

00:11:59.919 --> 00:12:02.080
Those nodes can be blocks.

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:05.960
They can be, so there is a set of blocks.

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:06.599
Here's a list.

00:12:06.599 --> 00:12:08.280
I won't go into detail in all of them.

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:09.719
There can be inlines.

00:12:09.719 --> 00:12:11.400
So the blocks are the containers.

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:14.000
And the inlines are usually the contents.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:18.320
And your Lua function can target any of these nodes.

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:21.520
So most of the AST types here that we see

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:24.440
are coming from the Pandoc API.

00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:26.359
And so you can find information on them

00:12:26.359 --> 00:12:28.679
on the Pandoc documentation.

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:32.359
But some of the blocks come also from custom AST nodes

00:12:32.359 --> 00:12:34.080
that we add into Quarto.

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:37.039
So the callouts, conditional blocks, and tapset,

00:12:37.039 --> 00:12:40.840
they are nodes that you can find in this abstract representation

00:12:40.840 --> 00:12:43.320
that are in relation to some of the features

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:45.280
you may know in Quarto, which are the callouts,

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:47.520
the conditional blocks, and the tapset, which are not

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:49.440
basic Pandoc features.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:51.719
And the documentation for those customized nodes

00:12:51.719 --> 00:12:53.400
are inside the Quarto documentation.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:55.119
So there is a bit of navigation.

00:12:55.119 --> 00:12:57.559
It's what, like, it's advanced documentation.

00:12:57.559 --> 00:13:00.760
But this is where you can find information on them.

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:02.840
Then you need some helpers function.

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:04.919
You need to write the processing of your filter.

00:13:04.919 --> 00:13:07.599
And for that, you have, like, three layers of API.

00:13:07.599 --> 00:13:10.200
You have the Lua base API, which are the base function

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:14.640
that Lua provides for string and link, pattern matching,

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:15.880
some table manipulation.

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:18.320
This is the basic from the language.

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:21.159
And then the second layer will be the Pandoc Lua API.

00:13:21.159 --> 00:13:23.960
So this is the core API that Pandoc

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:28.200
provides to work with the AST type that are

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:29.799
coming from Pandoc directly.

00:13:29.799 --> 00:13:31.840
But there is also some helpers function

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:36.320
to use with some of the specific features that Pandoc offers.

00:13:36.320 --> 00:13:38.599
And the third layers, you probably

00:13:38.599 --> 00:13:41.400
guessed right, is Quarto layers.

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:43.400
So there is a Quarto Lua API, where

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:45.159
we add additional function.

00:13:45.159 --> 00:13:47.719
Obviously, we add the necessary function

00:13:47.719 --> 00:13:51.080
to work with a custom AST type that Quarto is adding.

00:13:51.080 --> 00:13:52.640
But there are also useful function

00:13:52.640 --> 00:13:55.479
to work with the Quarto processing that

00:13:55.479 --> 00:13:58.000
has custom formats, things like that.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.880
And we also, as we own this layer of the Lua API,

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:04.400
we use that also to add some useful function that

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:07.880
is the Lua filter development.

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:10.200
So we keep adding some function into there.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:12.679
There are some function, for example, to add HTML

00:14:12.679 --> 00:14:14.760
dependencies, as you would do in R package,

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:15.760
for those who know that.

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:19.919
And you can do that to add things into there.

00:14:19.919 --> 00:14:22.479
And the last part is inserting, once you have your filter,

00:14:22.479 --> 00:14:25.679
is inserting that filter into the processing.

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:30.000
And the nice part of modifying or working

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:31.679
with the abstract representation is

00:14:31.679 --> 00:14:36.559
that you don't need to care that much about the raw output.

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:39.960
So you can make a different processing based on the format

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:40.679
that you target.

00:14:40.679 --> 00:14:42.640
But as you've seen in the two examples,

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:44.799
we didn't consider the format at all.

00:14:44.799 --> 00:14:48.919
And so for any format, the modification will happen.

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:54.039
And the Lua processing, the Quarto processing phase,

00:14:54.039 --> 00:14:58.119
Quarto offers different entry points for your processing.

00:14:58.119 --> 00:15:01.400
So you can have a look into that.

00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:02.719
So with that knowledge, you should

00:15:02.719 --> 00:15:08.159
be able to write some filters to solve your own function.

00:15:08.159 --> 00:15:11.119
And it's a bit natural to ask yourself,

00:15:11.119 --> 00:15:13.159
like you have this one-shot filter that you've made.

00:15:13.159 --> 00:15:16.239
And maybe you want to reuse it across your project.

00:15:16.239 --> 00:15:18.400
Or maybe you are working in an organization

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:21.119
where different users have the same problem.

00:15:21.119 --> 00:15:24.080
So the question of reusing these Lua filters makes sense.

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:25.840
And this is, at that point, that you

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:28.200
can consider Quarto extensions.

00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:32.679
They are a way to reuse and distribute

00:15:32.679 --> 00:15:34.599
some feature of Quarto.

00:15:34.599 --> 00:15:36.599
So filter is one of them.

00:15:36.599 --> 00:15:39.280
And you see that Quarto extension

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:40.320
can be of several forms.

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:41.400
There are also shortcodes.

00:15:41.400 --> 00:15:43.080
So with the knowledge of Lua function,

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:45.679
you can also write shortcodes.

00:15:45.679 --> 00:15:47.159
And there is other types.

00:15:47.159 --> 00:15:49.679
You can do extension for custom formats or brand.

00:15:49.679 --> 00:15:51.440
And they don't require knowing Lua at all.

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:54.760
But they are a way to ship that to several projects

00:15:54.760 --> 00:15:56.159
or several users.

00:15:56.159 --> 00:15:58.760
So with your filter, how would you do that?

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:01.400
You would use the Quarto create function

00:16:01.400 --> 00:16:05.320
to have the skeleton of the folder with all the file

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:05.840
you need.

00:16:05.840 --> 00:16:11.119
And you would copy your Lua filter into these organizations

00:16:11.119 --> 00:16:15.200
and configure in the YAML configuration in the right way.

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:19.719
And then you need to share it somewhere.

00:16:19.719 --> 00:16:22.840
And Quarto add a function to ease the distribution.

00:16:22.840 --> 00:16:24.679
This is the Quarto add function.

00:16:24.679 --> 00:16:27.280
And this function can work with extension

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:29.979
that are shared on a shared drive,

00:16:29.979 --> 00:16:32.599
for example, in your organization.

00:16:32.599 --> 00:16:35.400
It can work with extension that are shared online

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:37.400
as a zip in a URL.

00:16:37.400 --> 00:16:39.919
But the most common way to share extension

00:16:39.919 --> 00:16:41.840
will be through a remote GitHub repo.

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:44.760
And so Quarto add can also install from there.

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:46.719
So that way, you have one place where

00:16:46.719 --> 00:16:49.440
you can put your extension with your filters that

00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:50.559
solve your problem.

00:16:50.559 --> 00:16:53.000
And then it can be reused across project

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.119
by just using Quarto add and then calling the filter

00:16:56.119 --> 00:16:58.159
in the same way as we did before,

00:16:58.159 --> 00:17:00.239
just naming the filter you want to use

00:17:00.239 --> 00:17:02.359
for either your document or the full project.

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:09.119
And once you've done that, you have

00:17:09.119 --> 00:17:11.199
made a filter and a Quarto extension.

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:13.800
And you're probably not alone doing that.

00:17:13.839 --> 00:17:16.880
There is a full list of Quarto extension.

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:19.239
So this nice listing made by the community

00:17:19.239 --> 00:17:24.239
of all the Quarto extension that are hosted on GitHub.

00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:28.439
And some of them are for filters, as we discussed today.

00:17:28.439 --> 00:17:31.599
And so this is a great place if you have a problem

00:17:31.599 --> 00:17:33.160
and maybe you think someone else have it,

00:17:33.160 --> 00:17:35.500
you can look for a solution in there

00:17:35.500 --> 00:17:37.239
instead of doing your own.

00:17:37.239 --> 00:17:39.839
But if you start doing your own solution,

00:17:39.839 --> 00:17:42.439
then you can also go there to find examples

00:17:42.439 --> 00:17:45.800
of Lua filters out there, what function exists,

00:17:45.800 --> 00:17:47.280
how people do that.

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:49.880
And you see that some of those extension

00:17:49.880 --> 00:17:51.680
like Quarto Live are in this list

00:17:51.680 --> 00:17:53.160
and they are using Lua filters

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:55.199
to bring you those nice features.

00:17:58.479 --> 00:18:01.160
So I hope this talk give you the minimum

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:05.000
foundational knowledge to do consider really Lua filter

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.739
next time you feel stuck with something

00:18:06.739 --> 00:18:09.000
and you want to solve a very specific problem,

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:10.520
really go try it.

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:12.079
They are not that complicated.

00:18:12.599 --> 00:18:14.719
After all, they are just functions.

00:18:14.719 --> 00:18:18.439
And they can be useful to modify, replace, even remove,

00:18:18.439 --> 00:18:20.119
or maybe just for side effect

00:18:20.119 --> 00:18:23.900
because you have an insertion into the Quarto processing.

00:18:25.739 --> 00:18:26.640
So thank you.

00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:28.680
Hopefully you will now be able to read

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:31.000
those advanced documentation and understand a bit better.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:34.280
But feel free to reach out for any question now or after,

00:18:34.280 --> 00:18:37.000
or even later on social or GitHub.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:41.459
We have a discussion forum on the Quarto repo.

