00:18:56.920 --> 00:18:57.959
It's not,

00:18:57.959 --> 00:19:02.319
it was the aim of why I wanted to make this talk

00:19:02.319 --> 00:19:05.300
is that you don't need to start learning Lua

00:19:05.300 --> 00:19:07.040
before trying to do that

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:08.859
because of the example and things like that.

00:19:08.859 --> 00:19:11.420
But we do in the Quarto documentation,

00:19:11.420 --> 00:19:13.380
we do have a page dedicated.

00:19:13.380 --> 00:19:16.020
So it's hidden in the extension sections,

00:19:16.020 --> 00:19:18.579
but we have a page dedicated to Lua development

00:19:18.579 --> 00:19:21.819
where we try to guide you

00:19:21.819 --> 00:19:23.060
in what you need,

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:25.619
the basics you need to know to do your Lua filter.

00:19:25.619 --> 00:19:28.020
So you don't need to be a Lua developers.

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:30.380
You just need to need to write a function that does things

00:19:30.380 --> 00:19:32.579
and we provide API for that,

00:19:32.579 --> 00:19:35.140
useful functions and that.

00:19:35.140 --> 00:19:36.839
